    "source_sections": {
      "references": "",
      "remarks": "Even the case $k=3$ seems difficult. This may be true with the primes replaced by any set $A\\subseteq \\mathbb{N}$ such that\\[\\lvert A\\cap [1,N]\\rvert \\gg N/\\log N\\]and\\[\\sum_{\\substack{n\\in A\\\\ n\\leq N}}\\frac{1}{n} -\\log\\log N\\to \\infty\\]as $N\\to \\infty$.\n\nIf we weaken the question to ask for only almost all integers to be represented in this fashion then, for any $k\\geq 2$, any set $A$ such that $\\sum_{n\\in A}\\frac{1}{n}=\\infty$ has this property."
    },
